WEBVTT

00:06.173 --> 00:09.276 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Good evening.
I'm Hari Sreenivasan. Judy
Woodruff is away.

00:09.276 --> 00:13.513 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
On the "NewsHour" tonight:
Winter wallops the East Coast.
High winds, and heavy snow

00:13.513 --> 00:17.417 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
have cities from North Carolina
to New York shutting down.

00:17.417 --> 00:23.257 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Then: a clash over how to handle
a rise in feral cats in
communities across America.

00:23.257 --> 00:28.128 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ADITHYA SAMBAMURTHY, "Reveal":
Take Antioch, California, about
40 miles east of San Francisco.

00:28.128 --> 00:32.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The town is home to about 17,000
strays, one cat for every six
citizens.

00:32.933 --> 00:35.669 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And it's
Friday. David Brooks and Ruth
Marcus are in to analyze the
week's

00:35.669 --> 00:36.970 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
news.

00:36.970 --> 00:43.477 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
All that and more on
tonight's "PBS NewsHour."

00:43.477 --> 00:47.614 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
(BREAK)

00:47.614 --> 00:57.224 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: A blizzard is
bearing down tonight on
Washington, D.C., and states to

00:57.224 --> 01:01.862 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the north and south. The snow
moved in this afternoon,
shutting down schools,
government

01:01.862 --> 01:06.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
and transportation, and
canceling thousands of flights,
forecasters warning that, by
this

01:06.233 --> 01:11.738 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
time tomorrow, they will be
measuring in feet, instead of
inches.

01:11.738 --> 01:16.176 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
With store shelves nearly empty,
and road crews gearing up,
millions across the Eastern

01:16.176 --> 01:20.647 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
U.S. waited for the worst.
Forecasters are predicting one
of the biggest storms ever

01:20.647 --> 01:26.253 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the Mid-Atlantic especially,
with up to three inches of snow
an hour. As the wall

01:26.253 --> 01:30.624 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of weather closed in, blizzard
warnings or watches went up from
Arkansas and Tennessee,

01:30.624 --> 01:35.262 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
through Washington and as
far north as New York.

01:35.262 --> 01:39.232 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
About six inches of snow fell
overnight in the Little Rock,
Arkansas, area, breaking

01:39.232 --> 01:44.604 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a record set more than 20 years
ago. It shut down schools and
state government offices.

01:44.604 --> 01:49.710 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, in North Carolina, the snow
started falling before sunrise,
triggering a number of fatal

01:49.710 --> 01:51.411 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
wrecks.

01:51.411 --> 01:54.414 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GOV. PAT MCCRORY (R), North
Carolina: Where I'm seeing the
accidents is where it looks

01:54.414 --> 02:01.021 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
like it's a safe road, and
people are speeding, and because
they assume it's safe, because

02:01.021 --> 02:05.192 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they don't see snow on the
roads. And that's our greatest
concern right now.

02:05.192 --> 02:09.396 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: North Carolina
declared a state of emergency,
along with Tennessee,

02:09.396 --> 02:13.734 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Virginia, Maryland, and
Pennsylvania. So did the
nation's capital, sitting
squarely in

02:13.734 --> 02:17.738 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the blizzard's bullseye, with
estimates that more than two
feet of snow will fall.

02:17.738 --> 02:21.308 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MURIEL BOWSER (D), Mayor of
Washington, D.C.: I want to be
very clear with everybody. We

02:21.308 --> 02:28.849 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
see this as a major storm. It
has life and death implications,
and all the residents

02:28.849 --> 02:32.652 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of the district of Columbia
should treat it that way. We
have a forecast that I don't

02:32.652 --> 02:35.655 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
think we have had in 90 years.

02:35.655 --> 02:39.593 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: In a bid to
beat the storm, the federal
government closed all its
Washington

02:39.593 --> 02:43.730 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
offices at noon. And for the
first time, the city's entire
subway system planned to close

02:43.730 --> 02:46.967 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
for the weekend.

02:46.967 --> 02:52.773 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Meanwhile, all the major
airlines issued waivers for the
weekend, allowing passengers to
rebook

02:52.773 --> 02:57.744 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and avoid the storms. The snow
and high winds are expected to
continue into Sunday, amid

02:57.744 --> 03:01.715 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
