JUDY WOODRUFF: How
do you see this?

11:06.866 --> 11:09.969 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RUTH MARCUS: Well, I think
breakdown might be the operative
word.

11:09.969 --> 11:16.376 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And there is also this division
really between various pieces of
the Republican establishment.

11:16.376 --> 11:22.649 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The conservative Republican
establishment, as exemplified by
"National Review," is freaking

11:22.649 --> 11:26.853 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
out, I think, is the technical
term, about the Trump menace,
and that's the word that

11:26.853 --> 11:30.023 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
"National Review" used, menace.

11:30.023 --> 11:36.763 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Washington establishment and
the party establishment is
freaking out about Cruz,

11:36.763 --> 11:42.735 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
because they see, strangely,
Trump as -- some of them do --
we heard from Bob Dole this

11:42.735 --> 11:49.676 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
week -- Trump as more electable
than Cruz. They do not want to
have no shot at a third

11:49.676 --> 11:53.379 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
term in the White -- they don't
want to have a third Democratic
term in the White House.

11:53.379 --> 11:57.216 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, so,
but where does it go?

11:57.216 --> 12:04.123 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
David, you're saying that
Republicans are less tolerant or
less warm to the idea of

12:04.123 --> 12:08.027 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
conservatism. They're willing to
tolerate some chaos. But does
that mean -- does that

12:08.027 --> 12:11.764 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
automatically mean that Trump
prevails over these other
establishment candidates?

12:11.764 --> 12:15.001 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: Not automatically.

12:15.001 --> 12:20.039 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I'm still hoping the
establishment will get off their
rear ends and actually do
something

12:20.039 --> 12:24.143 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and act like an establishment
and rally behind one candidate.
But you have to say right now,

12:24.143 --> 12:27.146 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
given all the things that have
happened this weekend -- and,
remember, a lot can still

12:27.146 --> 12:31.951 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
happen between now and the
caucuses. The final week is like
70 percent of the campaign.

12:31.951 --> 12:38.491 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You could see massive swings.
And so you're looking for magic.
Who has magic right now?

12:38.491 --> 12:42.295 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And given all the things that
have happened, I don't think Bob
Dole gives Trump a lot of

12:42.295 --> 12:45.298 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
magic, but Sarah Palin gives
him a little. And to me...

12:45.298 --> 12:47.367 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You do think so?

12:47.367 --> 12:51.170 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: ... the vibe feels
a little like, if there is any
magic there, Trump has

12:51.170 --> 12:55.208 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a little of that magic, and
Cruz, even in the polls, is
falling slightly.

12:55.208 --> 12:58.011 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: How do you see
the Sarah Palin endorsement?

12:58.011 --> 13:03.850 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RUTH MARCUS: So, as a general
matter, endorsements don't
matter very much.

13:03.850 --> 13:09.989 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But this one, from that low
baseline, matters a little more
than most. First of all, once

13:09.989 --> 13:14.227 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
again, Donald Trump managed to
take attention away from
everybody else, including Ted
Cruz,

13:14.227 --> 13:16.329 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
who needs the attention more,
put it on him, Donald Trump.

13:16.329 --> 13:17.563 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: For several days.

13:17.563 --> 13:21.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
RUTH MARCUS: For several
days, and also Sarah Palin.

13:21.000 --> 13:25.805 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Also, to the extent that
endorsements matter, they matter
because they're validators of

13:25.805 --> 13:30.543 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
something that voters may still
have a question about. With
Donald Trump -- and this is the

13:30.543 --> 13:35.114 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
argument Ted Cruz has been
making -- the question is, is he
a real conservative, can you
really

13:35.114 --> 13:39.986 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
trust him to be a conservative,
not the guy with New York
values?

13:39.986 --> 13:45.425 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
With Sarah Palin, who may not be
convincing to Republicans inside
the Beltway, she can

13:45.425 --> 13:50.363 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
speak pretty convincingly to
voters in Iowa who, remember,
were for Rick Santorum four

13:50.363 --> 13:52.198 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
years ago.

13:52.198 --> 13:56.035 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But she also --
David, there are some voters who
say they absolutely don't

13:56.035 --> 13:59.338 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
trust her and don't
care what she thinks.

13:59.338 --> 14:02.809 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: And this is why we
shouldn't hand Trump the
nomination. There is a ceiling

14:02.809 --> 14:07.847 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
there. There is a real ceiling
there, especially as we get into
the more diverse states.

14:07.847 --> 14:14.454 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so I think, once you get an
establishment candidate, a
moderate candidate, what we now

14:14.454 --> 14:18.891 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
call moderate, Trump is still
very -- extremely vulnerable as
we get there. If you look at

14:18.891 --> 14:22.495 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
-- if you try to break down the
party into lanes, which may not
be valid anymore, but

14:22.495 --> 14:28.901 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
there's still 40, 50 percent who
are either moderate, have some
mixture of conservative

14:28.901 --> 14:32.071 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and liberal positions, who are
just party regulars, not
particularly ideological.

14:32.071 --> 14:35.575 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And those people, that's why
Romney has won. That's why
McCain has won. That's why Dole

14:35.575 --> 14:39.979 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
has won nominations. That's why
W. ran with compassionate
conservatism. They're still

14:39.979 --> 14:44.884 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
there. They haven't disappeared.
The party is radicalized,
clearly, but Trump and Cruz

14:44.884 --> 14:46.786 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
are both still vulnerable if
there's a single alternative.

14:46.786 --> 14:47.420 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well...

14:47.420 --> 14:47.754 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

14:47.754 --> 14:49.989 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Go ahead.

14:49.989 --> 14:53.626 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RUTH MARCUS: David said "once
you get," and I think that's the
operative term, because

14:53.626 --> 15:00.199 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
how in this time with super PACs
and so many candidates still
running in that -- for that

15:00.199 --> 15:04.170 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
moderate establishment, maybe
not moderate, but certainly
establishment mantle, how does

15:04.170 --> 15:06.506 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
that sort itself out?

15:06.506 --> 15:11.611 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's going to be difficult to
do. There is some -- a degree of
-- that can't be denied

15:11.611 --> 15:16.949 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of anti-Trump animus even with
the Republican Party. I have
heard it. I was with a bunch

15:16.949 --> 15:21.320 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of voters at a Ted Cruz event in
New Hampshire earlier this week,
and I was surprised at

15:21.320 --> 15:24.824 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the number of them who were not
shopping between Cruz and Trump.
Trump was totally off their

15:24.824 --> 15:26.426 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
list.

15:26.426 --> 15:28.661 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: One of the other
thing is the ads they're running
against each other.

15:28.661 --> 15:30.696 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And I was
going to ask you about it.

15:30.696 --> 15:35.268 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: And so I think the
Trump ads, they -- I mean,
personally, I find them
extremely

15:35.268 --> 15:39.539 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
noxious. They're extremely
anti-immigrant. And they attack
Cruz on two grounds, first,

15:39.539 --> 15:43.509 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
that he's insufficiently
anti-immigrant, and, second,
that he's kind of squirrelly and
there

15:43.509 --> 15:46.078 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are some images of him talking
to FOX News looking a little
squirrelly, and that he's

15:46.078 --> 15:47.046 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
opportunistic.

15:47.046 --> 15:49.515 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
JUDY WOODRUFF:
Squirrelly, meaning?

15:49.515 --> 15:53.553 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
DAVID BROOKS: That he
flip-flops, which he sort of did
on the immigration issue. He
took

15:53.553 --> 15:55.955 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
about a week when the
immigration reform was passing
to try to find the right
position

15:55.955 --> 15:59.225 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
for himself.

15:59.225 --> 16:04.230 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so that's the inauthenticity
and opportunism, where he's
weak. Cruz is hitting back with

16:04.230 --> 16:09.001 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
an ad charging Trump with being
a ruthless businessman. I don't
think that is an effective

16:09.001 --> 16:13.472 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
attack line. Donald Trump,
people sort of like that. And
so, if you just look at the

16:13.472 --> 16:15.341 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
two, the way they're ramping up
their campaigns right now,
again, Trump has a little
advantage

16:15.341 --> 16:17.844 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
in the ad wars, I would say.

16:17.844 --> 16:21.013 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And we haven't
talked much about ads in this
campaign, Ruth.

16:21.013 --> 16:25.351 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, in the last hours before
people vote, are these going to
make any difference?

16:25.351 --> 16:30.489 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RUTH MARCUS: Well, there have
not been really kind of breakout
ads that have galvanized

16:30.489 --> 16:34.293 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
attention in this campaign
more than in previous ones.

16:34.293 --> 16:38.331 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But there was an interesting one
that was just released last
night from the Bernie Sanders

16:38.331 --> 16:43.736 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
campaign, with which had this
very morning in America, if you
don't mind my using that

16:43.736 --> 16:45.338 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
phrase...

16:45.338 --> 16:46.305 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: From
Ronald Reagan.

16:46.305 --> 16:52.011 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RUTH MARCUS: ... with regard to
Bernie Sanders, tone to it. It
had zero message. From the

16:52.011 --> 16:57.817 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
guy who has a very crisp and
explicit message, it's just
Simon and Garfunkel America song

16:57.817 --> 17:02.321 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
with pictures of Bernie
Sanders and rapturous voters.

17:02.321 --> 17:06.659 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Could something
like that work? Because we're
seeing a much tougher race,

17:06.659 --> 17:09.228 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
not as tough as what the
Republicans are engaging in, but
we're seeing a much tougher race
now

17:09.228 --> 17:12.365 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
between Clinton and Sanders.

17:12.365 --> 17:16.369 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RUTH MARCUS: I watched it a few
times. I have to say, it made me
smile. And it made me also

17:16.369 --> 17:20.573 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
kind of have flashbacks
to Barack Obama 2008.

17:20.573 --> 17:26.312 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think Hillary Clinton may
be having some flashbacks now as
well, because, as with

17:26.312 --> 17:31.217 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Barack Obama, Sanders has turned
his campaign into quite a
movement. You see it with the

17:31.217 --> 17:35.288 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
voters in New Hampshire. And you
see it with the polls in New
Hampshire.

17:35.288 --> 17:40.760 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it's not that he has -- he
can afford to run that ad,
because it's not as if he

17:40.760 --> 17:44.096 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
lacks a message. Voters know
clearly what his message is.

17:44.096 --> 17:47.934 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But he also went
after her, David, in that debate
on Sunday night on several

17:47.934 --> 17:53.873 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
things, including the speaking
fees she collected from Wall
Street, from the big financial
firms.

17:53.873 --> 17:57.777 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Is that something that
gains traction for him?

17:57.777 --> 18:01.147 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: Among his voters
who think Wall Street is the
epicenter of evil, I think it

18:01.147 --> 18:03.115 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
is.

18:03.115 --> 18:09.455 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They also had an interesting
debate about health care reform.
And that was her making

18:09.455 --> 18:13.492 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
an incremental argument, we have
got to make our changes
gradually, and him making a
radical

18:13.492 --> 18:14.961 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
argument. And so it was
interesting. That was a
substantive, real argument about
how

18:14.961 --> 18:18.097 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
you change any system.

18:18.097 --> 18:23.336 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, again, I'm going to go back
to the magic -- or maybe a
better word is charisma. Some

18:23.336 --> 18:27.340 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
campaigns have charisma at
certain moments, and some
campaigns are flat in certain
moments.

18:27.340 --> 18:32.511 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Right now, in part, like that
ad, Sanders has a little more
charisma to her -- his campaign,

18:32.511 --> 18:34.513 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Clinton a little lacking in
charisma. And that's sort of
important, because people just

18:34.513 --> 18:38.384 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
gravitate in final days.

18:38.384 --> 18:43.522 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Even though he's
talking -- essentially, the
argument is whether you just
wipe away

18:43.522 --> 18:46.993 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to what we have done and you go
to a single-payer health care
system, which most Americans say

18:46.993 --> 18:49.328 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
they don't want, right, or...

18:49.328 --> 18:53.132 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RUTH MARCUS: Well, it really is
this argument about
practicality.

18:53.132 --> 18:57.003 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And one of the things that's
interesting is there is actually
a parallel argument going

18:57.003 --> 19:02.441 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
on in the Republican and
Democratic campaigns. So,
Hillary Clinton says, I'm the
pragmatist,

19:02.441 --> 19:07.413 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I'm a progressive, but I'm a
pragmatic one. I know how to get
results. What he's saying,

19:07.413 --> 19:12.218 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
maybe it's a great idea in
theory, but he will never be
able to put it in practice.

19:12.218 --> 19:18.357 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Oddly enough, Donald Trump is
making that same argument
against Ted Cruz. He is saying,

19:18.357 --> 19:22.728 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Ted Cruz, it can't -- well,
first of all, he's a little
squirrelly and maybe he's not

19:22.728 --> 19:27.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
really a conservative, and look
at this squirrelly answer on
immigration, but, also, Ted Cruz

19:27.833 --> 19:30.336 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
can't get anything done in
Washington because he doesn't
know how to get along with
anybody,

19:30.336 --> 19:33.305 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and he's too extreme.

19:33.305 --> 19:37.943 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so there is that sort of
practicality argument that is
emerging on both sides.

19:37.943 --> 19:41.080 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: It is
interesting, because you see
Bill Clinton out there, David,
making

19:41.080 --> 19:42.481 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
some of these same arguments.

19:42.481 --> 19:44.450 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And, Ruth, you saw him
on the trail this week.

19:44.450 --> 19:48.054 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RUTH MARCUS: I was with him. I
was having a little flashback
down memory lane. Bill

19:48.054 --> 19:51.257 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Clinton talked about stopping
off at the Dunkin' Donuts.

19:51.257 --> 19:56.695 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Does he have the
same -- does he bring the same
weight, gravitas to this

19:56.695 --> 19:59.465 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
campaign that he did in
the past, do you think?

19:59.465 --> 20:02.334 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: Yes. He's still
good. He's still a master at
arguing, master at making the

20:02.334 --> 20:04.703 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
case.

20:04.703 --> 20:09.375 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And there's a lot of residual
good will toward him. What's
striking to me is how, even he

20:09.375 --> 20:14.680 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ran as a -- and really governed
as a moderate, he still has
personal good will.

20:14.680 --> 20:18.551 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The other thing that's going on
is -- and I think this is also
helping Sanders in New

20:18.551 --> 20:22.354 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Hampshire -- and, again, I
wouldn't bet on him to win the
nomination -- but helping him,

20:22.354 --> 20:27.493 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Sanders, a little residual
resentment among Democratic
primary voters about Obama, and

20:27.493 --> 20:32.098 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
his being more centrist than
they would like, especially in
the first, say, six years.

20:32.098 --> 20:37.036 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so they're a little more
suspicious of moderation and are
more willing to take a

20:37.036 --> 20:38.771 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
flyer on a guy who may
not be that pragmatic.

20:38.771 --> 20:41.273 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Do you see that?

20:41.273 --> 20:46.412 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RUTH MARCUS: I actually felt a
lot of Obama love still there in
New Hampshire among the

20:46.412 --> 20:49.582 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
voters that I talked to.

20:49.582 --> 20:54.787 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I think Bill Clinton,
especially among Democratic
primary voters and especially in

20:54.787 --> 21:01.193 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
New Hampshire, which was a state
that has showered both Clintons
with love and success

21:01.193 --> 21:03.896 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
-- well, you know, he didn't win
the New Hampshire primary, but
he came in second -- is a
valuable

21:03.896 --> 21:05.764 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
tool.

21:05.764 --> 21:10.569 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think the really important
question for us all to be
thinking about going forward

21:10.569 --> 21:14.340 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is, what if? What if what once
seemed unimaginable happens,
Bernie Sanders wins both Iowa
and

21:14.340 --> 21:14.740 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
New Hampshire?

21:14.740 --> 21:16.509 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Right. Right.

21:16.509 --> 21:21.514 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
RUTH MARCUS: The Clinton
campaign argument is the
demographic fire wall of
minority voters

21:21.514 --> 21:26.852 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in South Carolina and beyond.
The Sanders campaign argument is
the kind of magic that

21:26.852 --> 21:30.823 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
David's been talking about and
whether people will be --
whether that demographic
firewall

21:30.823 --> 21:34.326 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is as strong as the Clinton
campaign thinks it is.

21:34.326 --> 21:36.729 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Less than 30
