RUTH MARCUS: Same to you.

22:11.931 --> 22:23.809 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Next: a big
finding and discovery in space
that has astronomers and

22:23.809 --> 22:26.412 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
plenty of other people excited.

22:26.412 --> 22:28.981 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Jeffrey Brown has
our conversation.

22:28.981 --> 22:33.619 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Nine planets in
the solar system, right? That's
what most of us grew up
thinking.

22:33.619 --> 22:39.625 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Well, that ended in 2006, when
Pluto was downgraded to a dwarf
planet.

22:39.625 --> 22:43.829 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But now comes news that there
might be a ninth planet after
all. Researchers at the
California

22:43.829 --> 22:49.568 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Institute of Technology found
evidence of a planet with a mass
10 times that of Earth.

22:49.568 --> 22:53.973 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
One of the Caltech astronomers,
Mike Brown, joins us now. And I
will add that he is also

22:53.973 --> 22:57.876 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
known as the chief culprit in
lowering Pluto's status. His
memoir is titled "How I Killed

22:57.876 --> 23:01.213 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Pluto and Why It Had It Coming."

23:01.213 --> 23:04.583 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, sort of making amends
here I guess, Mike Brown?

23:04.583 --> 23:07.653 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MIKE BROWN, California Institute
of Technology: You know, it's --
I don't think of it that

23:07.653 --> 23:11.624 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
way. I think of it as, this is
something I have been working at
for 20 years, and Pluto

23:11.624 --> 23:14.960 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
was just collateral
damage along the way.

23:14.960 --> 23:19.565 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: All right, so
let's be as clear as we can
about what you have done here.
You

23:19.565 --> 23:24.603 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have not seen this new planet,
right? This is something you
surmise. Explain to us.

23:24.603 --> 23:27.072 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MIKE BROWN: Yes, that's
absolutely right, and it's
important to know that we -- no
one

23:27.072 --> 23:30.009 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
has actually seen
this planet yet.

23:30.009 --> 23:37.216 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What we have done is felt it,
or, more precisely, we have seen
its gravitational effect on the

23:37.216 --> 23:42.788 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
most distant things in the solar
system. And from those
gravitational effects, we can
tell

23:42.788 --> 23:47.760 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that it must be out there. And
this is the same way that
Neptune, for example, was
discovered,

23:47.760 --> 23:51.463 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
by its gravitational effects on
Uranus. So, there's a long
history of this sort of
astronomy.

23:51.463 --> 23:55.234 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You're seeing
gravitational effects on several
-- I gather, six small

23:55.234 --> 23:56.435 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
bodies out there?

23:56.435 --> 23:59.571 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MIKE BROWN: There is actually
quite a big collection.

23:59.571 --> 24:03.509 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There are six that are doing one
thing. There are five more that
are doing something else.

24:03.509 --> 24:07.546 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then there's another eight
doing something. When you put
them all together, it's a pretty

24:07.546 --> 24:12.184 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
big population that are going in
directions and moving in ways
that they shouldn't be

24:12.184 --> 24:15.654 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
doing unless there is something
organizing the whole pattern.

24:15.654 --> 24:17.890 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, this is -- I
don't know if this is a silly
question, but this is what

24:17.890 --> 24:24.797 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
confused me. If you can see --
or can see those bodies, why can
you not see the planet,

24:24.797 --> 24:26.832 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
if you know those bodies
are there for sure?

24:26.832 --> 24:30.536 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MIKE BROWN: Yes, so that's
a really good question.

24:30.536 --> 24:35.874 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The planet -- the effect of the
planet can be felt by probably
many thousands of bodies

24:35.874 --> 24:39.845 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that are out there. We have only
found the first score of them.
But there must be many

24:39.845 --> 24:44.483 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
thousands out there. So it's a
lot easier to look in a random
direction in space and

24:44.483 --> 24:49.855 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
see something that has been
affected by this planet than to
immediately go and find it.

24:49.855 --> 24:54.760 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, right now, we know the
orbital path of the planet
through the sky, but we don't
know

24:54.760 --> 24:58.063 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
where in the orbital path it is,
so we're setting out on a grand
search to try to find

24:58.063 --> 24:59.631 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
it.

24:59.631 --> 25:02.668 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Well, so what --
if it is a planet, what do --
what else you know about

25:02.668 --> 25:08.674 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it in terms of size, mass, why
it's so far away from the other
known planets?

25:08.674 --> 25:13.746 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MIKE BROWN: It's actually --
having not seen it, we actually
know quite a good bit about

25:13.746 --> 25:16.849 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
it, or we have inferred
quite a good bit about it.

25:16.849 --> 25:21.387 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So we know that it's about 10
times the mass of the Earth. It
has to be that big to have

25:21.387 --> 25:25.958 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
had the gravitational influence
over such a long distance that
it has. And at 10 times

25:25.958 --> 25:28.961 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the mass of the Earth, that
makes it a little bit smaller
than Neptune.

25:28.961 --> 25:34.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, we think it's probably a
miniature Neptune. It's probably
a gas giant like Neptune. It

25:34.533 --> 25:41.240 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
has no solid surface, just a gas
surface. And it has this crazy
elliptical orbit. It

25:41.240 --> 25:46.311 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
takes 10,000 to 20,000 years to
go around the sun. And the
closest it ever gets to the

25:46.311 --> 25:53.185 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
sun is about 20 billion miles,
which, to put it in context, is
-- it's something like five

25:53.185 --> 25:57.055 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
times further than the
distance that Pluto is right.

25:57.055 --> 26:01.760 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But on that 10,000-year journey
around the sun, it goes out to
100 billion miles, which

26:01.760 --> 26:06.331 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is about 25 times the distance
of Pluto. So, it's really quite
a long ways out there and

26:06.331 --> 26:08.901 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
on quite an extended orbit.

26:08.901 --> 26:12.805 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: This is not, of
course, the first time that
astronomers have suspected

26:12.805 --> 26:18.710 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the presence of a phantom planet
at the outer edges of the solar
system, right? There is

26:18.710 --> 26:21.280 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
reason to be more
confident this time?

26:21.280 --> 26:25.784 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MIKE BROWN: Yes, so, actually,
the idea that there is another
planet out beyond Neptune

26:25.784 --> 26:30.355 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
or beyond Pluto, when Pluto was
a planet, has a long and, I
would say, fairly sordid

26:30.355 --> 26:32.825 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
history over the past
hundred years, really.

26:32.825 --> 26:34.927 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

26:34.927 --> 26:38.730 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MIKE BROWN: Every time
astronomers would see something
that they didn't quite
understand

26:38.730 --> 26:41.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the outer part of the solar
system, the immediate thing that
everybody jumps to is

26:41.233 --> 26:43.368 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
must be a planet.

26:43.368 --> 26:48.073 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, you can go back really over
the last century and read all
these different accounts of why

26:48.073 --> 26:52.911 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
there must be a planet. Every
single one of them has turned
out to be wrong. Usually,

26:52.911 --> 26:55.914 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it's that the data they were
looking at were incorrect.
Sometimes, they were
misinterpreting

26:55.914 --> 26:59.184 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
data. But they have
always been wrong.

26:59.184 --> 27:03.422 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, we're saying, yes, for 100
years, everybody's been wrong,
but we're, of course, right.

27:03.422 --> 27:04.990 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

27:04.990 --> 27:08.227 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Of course. I
will go with you for now.

27:08.227 --> 27:15.801 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, also, this made me think
about, and for the layman, how
this kind of science is done.

27:15.801 --> 27:23.008 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Right? This is always a mix of
theory and observing, that they
both work hand in hand?

27:23.008 --> 27:26.612 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MIKE BROWN: Yes, this has
actually been -- that mix is
personified in the two of us
have been

27:26.612 --> 27:28.981 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
working on this problem.

27:28.981 --> 27:33.886 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, it's me. I'm primarily an
observational astronomer. I look
at the sky and try to figure

27:33.886 --> 27:38.757 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
out what's going on. My
colleague, who I think did the
heavy lifting here, is
Konstantin

27:38.757 --> 27:45.531 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Batygin. He is a theorist. He
understands the gravitational
dynamics in gory detail.

27:45.531 --> 27:49.935 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And he and I are four doors down
from each other at Caltech. And
we would be running

27:49.935 --> 27:54.039 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
back and forth across the
hallways for the past two years,
really. I would bring in some

27:54.039 --> 27:58.243 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
more observational constraints.
He would think about it, put it
in the computer, write the

27:58.243 --> 28:01.413 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
equations. We would talk to
each other. We would argue.

28:01.413 --> 28:06.385 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's -- these two different
viewpoints, I think, were
critical to really making this

28:06.385 --> 28:09.021 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
realization that there has
to be this planet out there.

28:09.021 --> 28:13.825 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Well, so what
happens next? How will
scientists verify its existence?

28:13.825 --> 28:16.562 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Do you ultimately
have to see it?

28:16.562 --> 28:20.165 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MIKE BROWN: You have to see it.

28:20.165 --> 28:25.971 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Right now, any good scientist is
going to be skeptical, because
it's a pretty big claim.

28:25.971 --> 28:30.208 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And without the final evidence
that it's real, there is always
that chance that it's not.

28:30.208 --> 28:35.180 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
So, everybody should be
skeptical. But I think it's time
to mount this search.

28:35.180 --> 28:41.053 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I mean, we like to think of it
as, we have provided the
treasure map of where this ninth

28:41.053 --> 28:47.092 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
planet is, and we have done the
starting gun, and now it's a
race to actually point your

28:47.092 --> 28:52.130 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
telescope at the right spot in
the sky and make that discovery
of planet nine.

28:52.130 --> 28:55.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: All right, Mike
Brown of Caltech, thanks so
much, and good luck.

28:55.233 --> 29:03.508 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
MIKE BROWN: Thank you.
It's been a pleasure.

29:03.508 --> 29:15.988 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Tonight: an
innovative solution to bridging
the digital divide for students.

29:15.988 --> 29:19.992 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Too frequently, kids and their
parents in rural low-income
communities don't have access

29:19.992 --> 29:24.896 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to the Internet and high-quality
learning technologies. But, in
California, a unique

29:24.896 --> 29:31.136 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
project is providing free home
access to the Web in one of the
nation's poorest districts.

29:31.136 --> 29:34.940 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Much of the footage for this
story was shot by teenagers who
are part of our Student
Reporting

29:34.940 --> 29:39.044 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Labs network, in collaboration
with PBS SoCal in Southern
California.

29:39.044 --> 29:42.247 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
The correspondent
is David Nazar.

29:42.247 --> 29:47.519 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID NAZAR: Thirty minutes west
of the wealthy suburbs of Palm
Springs is a desert oasis

29:47.519 --> 29:52.858 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
best known its annual Coachella
Valley Music and Arts Festival.

29:52.858 --> 29:57.863 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But behind the parties and
concerts stretches a vast and
isolated landscape, home to the

29:57.863 --> 30:01.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
second poorest school district
in the country, where most
families live below the poverty

30:01.533 --> 30:04.403 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
line and struggle
just to pay the rent.

30:04.403 --> 30:06.405 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DARRYL ADAMS, Superintendent,
Coachella Valley Unified School
District: We have some of the

30:06.405 --> 30:11.176 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
poorest of the poor in our
country, very economically
challenged, and 100 percent of
our students

30:11.176 --> 30:16.148 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are on free and reduced lunch.
Some of them living at trailer
home parks that some have

30:16.148 --> 30:21.053 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
been condemned recently, or some
in railroad, abandoned railroad
cars. It's just unbelievable,

30:21.053 --> 30:23.288 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
some of the
challenges they face.

30:23.288 --> 30:28.260 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID NAZAR: Coachella Valley
Unified School District
Superintendent Darryl Adams
believes

30:28.260 --> 30:32.164 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the right use of technology is
critical for the families in
this area, like Norma Olivas

30:32.164 --> 30:35.167 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and her daughter, Anisa Perez.

30:35.167 --> 30:41.206 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NORMA OLIVAS, Mother: I do see
students sometimes struggling,
and, right now, sometimes, some

30:41.206 --> 30:45.377 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of the kids struggling to get
school, to do certain things.
And I wouldn't want my daughter

30:45.377 --> 30:48.847 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to go through any that. I
wouldn't want her to be a
dropout.

30:48.847 --> 30:54.152 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID NAZAR: When Adams took the
job in 2011, the graduation rate
was 70 percent, according

30:54.152 --> 30:58.190 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to the district. One of his key
initiatives was to get every
student an iPad and Wi-Fi

30:58.190 --> 31:01.326 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
service, but he knew
it would be challenge.

31:01.326 --> 31:06.798 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DARRYL ADAMS: We have 1,250
square miles to cover, larger
than the state of Rhode Island.

31:06.798 --> 31:10.135 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, when we out there were spots
in every which way, students
weren't connected, we

31:10.135 --> 31:13.004 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
said, well, how can we
get them connected?

31:13.004 --> 31:16.541 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so one of the ways, we said,
look, we got 100 buses. Let's
put Wi-Fi routers on

31:16.541 --> 31:21.046 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
those buses. And let's park
them where the need is.

31:21.046 --> 31:26.418 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID NAZAR: Finding the funding
for this fleet of buses was no
easy tasks. Nevertheless,

31:26.418 --> 31:33.325 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
