36:40.665 --> 36:44.069 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And now a story about cats, not
the ones living in homes, but
stray and feral cats that live

36:44.069 --> 36:46.704 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
outside.

36:46.704 --> 36:50.675 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
By some estimates, there are 80
million feral cats in this
country. And the question of

36:50.675 --> 36:54.813 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
how to control them is sparking
controversy. Animal rights
activists, who want to save

36:54.813 --> 36:59.651 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
stray cats, say there is an
alternative to euthanizing feral
cats, a method they say

36:59.651 --> 37:05.356 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
will control the cat population
that's more humane and
effective. But will it work.

37:05.356 --> 37:07.792 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Adithya Sambamurthy from our
partner "Reveal" at the Center
for Investigative Reporting

37:07.792 --> 37:11.029 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
has the story.

37:11.029 --> 37:14.833 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ADITHYA SAMBAMURTHY, "Reveal":
Americans have long been
obsessed with cats in
commercials,

37:14.833 --> 37:18.803 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
cartoons and, of course,
on the Internet.

37:18.803 --> 37:25.243 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But for every cat in our homes,
there's a stray one on the
loose, roaming parking lots,

37:25.243 --> 37:30.949 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
alleyways, fields and backyards.
They're everywhere, and,
increasingly, it's a problem.

37:30.949 --> 37:35.453 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Take Antioch, California, about
40 miles east of San Francisco.
The town is home to about

37:35.453 --> 37:40.825 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
17,000 strays, one cat
for every six citizens.

37:40.825 --> 37:43.862 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
At the local animal shelter,
Monika Helgemo is overwhelmed.

37:43.862 --> 37:47.132 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MONIKA HELGEMO, Animal Shelter:
This one's here obviously is
saying, pet me, pet me.

37:47.132 --> 37:56.841 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This cat here, see the ears
go back? That's a feral cat.

37:56.841 --> 37:58.810 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ADITHYA SAMBAMURTHY: Feral cats
like this one are basically wild
animals, and so they're

37:58.810 --> 38:01.346 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
not candidates for adoption.

38:01.346 --> 38:05.049 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MONIKA HELGEMO: We will do what
we can and see if we can find a
place for her and go

38:05.049 --> 38:08.987 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
live her life. If not, we're
going to end up having to put
her to sleep, euthanize her.

38:08.987 --> 38:14.425 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ADITHYA SAMBAMURTHY: Antioch is
typical. There are an estimated
80 million stray and feral

38:14.425 --> 38:19.731 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
cats in the U.S. Traditionally,
the only way to deal with this
overpopulation was to euthanize

38:19.731 --> 38:25.003 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
them. More than a million cats
are killed in animal shelters
every year. And that's

38:25.003 --> 38:28.039 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
made some cat lovers so mad,
they have gotten organized.

38:28.039 --> 38:30.642 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ACTIVIST: Are you guys ready
to save some more cats?

38:30.642 --> 38:32.977 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
(CHEERING AND APPLAUSE)

38:32.977 --> 38:37.515 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ADITHYA SAMBAMURTHY: This is a
national gathering of feral cat
advocates near Washington, D.C.

38:37.515 --> 38:41.419 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's hosted by Alley Cat Allies.
They run a network of a
quarter-million activists that

38:41.419 --> 38:44.022 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
fight for feral cats.

38:44.022 --> 38:45.123 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BECKY ROBINSON, Founder and
President, Alley Cat Allies: We
changed the community. We
brought

38:45.123 --> 38:51.763 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
neighbors together. We
changed cat care forever.

38:51.763 --> 38:57.502 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ADITHYA SAMBAMURTHY: Becky
Robinson is the founder and
president of Alley Cat Allies.

38:57.502 --> 39:04.075 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She helped pioneer a population
control method called trap,
neuter, return, or TNR.

39:04.075 --> 39:06.077 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Instead of killing them, it's
about sterilizing cats and
letting them live the rest of
their

39:06.077 --> 39:08.513 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
lives outdoors.

39:08.513 --> 39:12.817 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BECKY ROBINSON: Trap, neuter,
return for feral cats works. And
what we mean when we say it

39:12.817 --> 39:17.789 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
works is that it stops the
breeding of a cat, so there's no
more litters of kittens.

39:17.789 --> 39:22.694 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ADITHYA SAMBAMURTHY: In Antioch,
Susan Smith shows me how trap,
neuter, return is done.

39:22.694 --> 39:27.365 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She's supported by Alley Cat
Allies, and she's trying to get
the city to embrace TNR.

39:27.365 --> 39:35.340 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SUSAN SMITH, Activist: I'm going
to bait the trap with some wet
food, and then some tuna,

39:35.340 --> 39:39.811 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
some albacore.

39:39.811 --> 39:45.850 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ADITHYA SAMBAMURTHY: The cats
are spayed or neutered at a
local clinic, given rabies
shots,

39:45.850 --> 39:50.521 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and the tips of their ears are
removed to show that they have
been fixed.

39:50.521 --> 39:57.629 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Then Smith returns them back to
the streets where they were
trapped. She continues to

39:57.629 --> 40:02.467 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
feed them in what are known as
cat colonies. The feeding is
key. Without it, she couldn't

40:02.467 --> 40:07.672 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
attract other cats in the area
to trap them and get them fixed.

40:07.672 --> 40:13.077 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TNR is catching on. More than
400 cities and counties have
adopted this method over the

40:13.077 --> 40:18.149 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
past 25 years. Even pet products
retailers have signed on,
creating nonprofits that have

40:18.149 --> 40:22.820 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
donated millions of
dollars to TNR groups.

40:22.820 --> 40:26.691 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Bryan Kortis spent the last five
years managing TNR grants for
PetSmart Charities.

40:26.691 --> 40:31.229 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
BRYAN KORTIS, PetSmart
Charities: PetSmart Charities,
in wanting to end cat
overpopulation,

40:31.229 --> 40:35.199 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
has embraced trap, neuter,
return as the most effective way
to make that happen.

40:35.199 --> 40:38.836 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ADITHYA SAMBAMURTHY: TNR's
expansion alarms wildlife
conservation groups.

40:38.836 --> 40:41.839 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GRANT SIZEMORE, American Bird
Conservancy: This is an emerging
conservation crisis.

40:41.839 --> 40:44.909 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ADITHYA SAMBAMURTHY: Grant
Sizemore directs the invasive
species programs at the American

40:44.909 --> 40:47.545 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Bird Conservancy in
Washington, D.C.

40:47.545 --> 40:53.151 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GRANT SIZEMORE: There were zero
domestic cats in North America
in 1492, which means that

40:53.151 --> 40:58.723 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we now have well over 100
million invasive predators
roaming the landscape, killing
wildlife.

40:58.723 --> 41:02.093 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ADITHYA SAMBAMURTHY: Sizemore
cites a study from the
Smithsonian Conservation Biology

41:02.093 --> 41:07.365 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Institute that estimates cats
kill around 2.4 billion birds
and 12.3 billion mammals

41:07.365 --> 41:10.668 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
every year.

41:10.668 --> 41:14.739 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
On Jekyll Island in Southern
Georgia, Dr. Sonia Hernandez and
her research team are

41:14.739 --> 41:19.344 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
seeing this from the cats'
perspective. They're putting
cameras on cats.

41:19.344 --> 41:23.948 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DR. SONIA HERNANDEZ, University
of Georgia: So far, we have been
able to collar 31 cats.

41:23.948 --> 41:27.719 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We know that a majority of them
do hunt, despite the fact that
they get fed.

41:27.719 --> 41:32.457 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ADITHYA SAMBAMURTHY: The cat
camera footage shows that even
well-fed cats in TNR programs

41:32.457 --> 41:41.265 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
hunt anything they can get their
paws on. They're just hard-wired
to hunt. And the food

41:41.265 --> 41:45.670 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
used to attract the cats and
trap them also draws in other
predators that can cause
problems.

41:45.670 --> 41:50.541 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Raccoons, skunks, and possums
compete with the cats for food.

41:50.541 --> 41:55.646 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DR. SONIA HERNANDEZ: We want to
be very careful that we don't
encourage a lot of wildlife

41:55.646 --> 42:02.687 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
coming together, sharing
pathogens, and then potentially
bringing that to people.

42:02.687 --> 42:06.290 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ADITHYA SAMBAMURTHY: Back in
Antioch, California, public
health concerns prompted the
city to

42:06.290 --> 42:09.427 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
propose a ban on feeding
cats on public property.

42:09.427 --> 42:12.263 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
WOMAN: The cats are not
the villains in this.

42:12.263 --> 42:14.665 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ADITHYA SAMBAMURTHY: There
was stiff opposition.

42:14.665 --> 42:19.804 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GIRL: They don't deserve to
starve. They deserve to have a
right to live.

42:19.804 --> 42:23.307 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN: I'm not afraid of a cat
urinating on my foot. I'm afraid
of the meth heads that

42:23.307 --> 42:26.377 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
