The city council granted Susan
Smith and her allies

45:14.612 --> 45:21.886 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the right to feed as part of an
official trap, neuter and return
program.

45:21.886 --> 45:26.824 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When it comes to controlling
cats, it's not only about
science. It's about our
emotions.

45:26.824 --> 45:31.762 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And in the court of public
opinion, it seems that America
will always back the cat.

45:31.762 --> 45:36.267 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For "PBS NewsHour," I'm Adithya
Sambamurthy in Antioch,
California.

45:36.267 --> 45:41.038 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And, earlier
this week, I was in New York and
spoke with Adithya Sambamurthy.

45:41.038 --> 45:45.076 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
As your piece points out, there
is still some question about the
effectiveness of this approach.

45:45.076 --> 45:48.512 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, why are companies and
charities putting money behind
it?

45:48.512 --> 45:52.516 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ADITHYA SAMBAMURTHY: Well, it's
a good question. And it's one
that I put to PetSmart
Charities.

45:52.516 --> 45:58.856 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the response that I got is
that the founders of the company
want to end homelessness -- cat

45:58.856 --> 46:02.994 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
homelessness. They want to end
the euthanasia of cats in
shelters. And they believe that

46:02.994 --> 46:06.030 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
this is the best approach.

46:06.030 --> 46:10.901 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When you look at it through
strictly a, you know, animal
rights, animal welfare
perspective,

46:10.901 --> 46:15.206 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think there is something to be
said for it. The problem is
that, at the city level,

46:15.206 --> 46:19.343 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
at county level, when you're
talking about many thousands of
cats, the research just

46:19.343 --> 46:22.179 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
doesn't show that it's
working at that level.

46:22.179 --> 46:26.183 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: OK, so let's
talk about the societal impact.
How significant of a

46:26.183 --> 46:29.253 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
problem is this in
different communities?

46:29.253 --> 46:33.290 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ADITHYA SAMBAMURTHY: The study
that I reference is the
University of Georgia's cat
camera

46:33.290 --> 46:38.295 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
study. And what's really
interesting here is that, even
if you feed cats on a daily

46:38.295 --> 46:41.432 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
basis and you spay and neuter
them, they are still going to go
out and hunt. They're
instinctual

46:41.432 --> 46:44.435 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
predators.

46:44.435 --> 46:49.273 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The University of Georgia shows
that cats are not just killing
mice and rats. They're

46:49.273 --> 46:56.047 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
killing frogs, a surprising
number of them, reptiles,
amphibians, small mammals, and
birds.

46:56.047 --> 47:00.051 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so if you have vulnerable
species in your community, it's
a problem.

47:00.051 --> 47:07.024 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Is there any
way to domesticate a feral cat
if you catch them young enough?

47:07.024 --> 47:12.630 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ADITHYA SAMBAMURTHY: Yes, I did
that. We -- I have adopted a
kitten that was born to a feral

47:12.630 --> 47:16.467 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
mother. And he's doing really
well and he loves humans.

47:16.467 --> 47:22.139 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So he's definitely tame now.
But, for adult feral cats, it's
very rare. And it's not a

47:22.139 --> 47:25.209 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
policy prescription. We're not
going to adopt our way out of
this problem.

47:25.209 --> 47:27.945 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: You talk a
little bit about the law of
large numbers here. How do you

47:27.945 --> 47:33.117 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
