48:31.642 --> 48:36.447 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What better way to battle
discrimination than with pop
culture? Or so thought Haroon
Moghul,

48:36.447 --> 48:41.218 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
when he asked J.J. Abrams in an
open letter to add an Islamic
character to "Star Wars."

48:41.218 --> 48:43.988 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Here's more of his thoughts on
why a Jedi named Mohammad could
help fight fear with

48:43.988 --> 48:46.157 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
hope.

48:46.157 --> 48:49.860 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HAROON MOGHUL, Author: The day
before "The Force Awakens" was
released, I wrote an open

48:49.860 --> 48:54.598 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
letter to its director, J.J.
Abrams, who also rebooted "Star
Trek."

48:54.598 --> 48:58.669 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
With tensions between Muslims
and our neighbors worse than I
had ever known, I asked Abrams

48:58.669 --> 49:01.972 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
to add a positive Muslim
character to one of these
franchises, maybe, I mused, a
Jedi

49:01.972 --> 49:05.409 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
named Mohammed.

49:05.409 --> 49:08.979 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But many readers were
dismissive. One wrote simply
that Star Wars was set a long
time

49:08.979 --> 49:14.285 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ago in a galaxy far, far away,
where Islam doesn't exist.

49:14.285 --> 49:19.590 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
By missing my point, he made my
point. We can accept a Ben
Kenobi, though Ben's a Hebrew

49:19.590 --> 49:23.994 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
name. We don't seem to have any
trouble with Luke Skywalker,
even though Luke was also

49:23.994 --> 49:29.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
one of the 12 apostles. Captain
Jim Kirk, great, but a Captain
Hussein Kirk, that made

49:29.533 --> 49:33.938 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
some readers think I wanted
Sharia law on the bridge, when I
had said no such thing.

49:33.938 --> 49:40.044 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I only wanted us to confront how
we treat Muslims. Islamophobia
is real, and it's ugly.

49:40.044 --> 49:42.813 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Robert Doggart allegedly planned
to attack Muslims in New York
with guns, bombs, even

49:42.813 --> 49:44.882 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a machete.

49:44.882 --> 49:51.622 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A former Klan member, Glendon
Crawford, tried to build a
radioactive weapon to attack
mosques.

49:51.622 --> 49:57.294 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
People have been kicked,
punched, stabbed, shot,
murdered, even pushed in front
of trains,

49:57.294 --> 50:01.098 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
targeted for their faith
and their faith alone.

50:01.098 --> 50:05.936 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Islamophobia is like racism, not
because Islam is a race, but
because, for anti-Muslim bigots,

50:05.936 --> 50:10.708 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Islam functions in the exact
same way that race does for
racists.

50:10.708 --> 50:15.446 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That doesn't mean I deny the
terrible violence committed by
some Muslims, sometimes in
Islam's

50:15.446 --> 50:19.516 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
name. That doesn't mean I don't
respect everyone's right to
contest ideas and beliefs they
don't

50:19.516 --> 50:25.122 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
agree with, including my own. It
just means I think judging every
single Muslim by the

50:25.122 --> 50:28.792 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
actions of a few, especially
when nearly every Muslim
institution and organization
condemns

50:28.792 --> 50:33.163 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
those actions, is a problem.

50:33.163 --> 50:37.701 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What someone thinks of Islam
depends a lot on whether she
knows any Muslims. The challenge

50:37.701 --> 50:43.641 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is that, out of 322 million
Americans, only a few million
are Muslim. Even in a
transporter,

50:43.641 --> 50:46.277 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
how could we meet and greet
everyone in time to change
minds?

50:46.277 --> 50:52.683 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That is why I wrote that letter
to J.J. Abrams in The Washington
Post. Science fiction and

50:52.683 --> 50:57.288 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
fantasy, whether books or
movies, are an astonishingly
effective ways to reach huge
numbers of people,

50:57.288 --> 51:01.725 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to reflect us back to ourselves,
and to provoke us to think
differently.

51:01.725 --> 51:05.996 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The original "Star Trek"
featured an African
communications officer, a
Russian navigator

51:05.996 --> 51:10.768 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and a Japanese helmsman, not to
mention a half-Vulcan,
half-human first officer. That

51:10.768 --> 51:16.307 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
was back in the 1960s, during
the civil rights era, at the
height of the Cold War, just a

51:16.307 --> 51:20.577 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
few decades from Japanese
internment camps. Yet the
television show was wildly
popular,

51:20.577 --> 51:25.149 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and it still is, as are the many
spinoffs that grew out of it.

51:25.149 --> 51:29.219 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It didn't matter where all those
characters came from, but where
they were going, where

51:29.219 --> 51:33.223 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
no one had gone before. It gave
us a vision for our divided
planet, of a united future

51:33.223 --> 51:36.660 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
we could want, not dread.

51:36.660 --> 51:42.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Can we see someone of a Muslim
background being part of that
future too? I hope so.

51:42.166 --> 51:46.337 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
People often ask me, how can
ordinary folks fight extremism
and intolerance? I tell them,

51:46.337 --> 51:50.441 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
by imagining a world that's not
just different, but better. You
don't fight fear with fear.

51:50.441 --> 52:07.057 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You fight fear with hope.

52:07.057 --> 52:10.527 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: On the
